## Why does this problem occur?

The issue occurs because of the differences in how Java&#39;s `Date` class and the newer `java.time.LocalDate` class are serialized and deserialized when working with JSON libraries like FeignClient.

When you use the `java.time.LocalDate` class, you&#39;re using a more modern date representation that aligns well with ISO-8601 date formats, which are widely recognized and supported in JSON serialization libraries. `LocalDate` is designed to work seamlessly with JSON serialization, which is why you&#39;re not encountering any errors.

The error you initially encountered, `&quot;java.time.format.DateTimeParseException: Text &#39;1692738000000&#39; could not be parsed at index 0&quot;`, suggests that the value `&#39;1692738000000&#39;` is not recognized as a valid date string by the default parsing logic for the `Date` class. JSON serialization libraries expect date strings to be in a specific format, and when the value doesn&#39;t conform to that format, parsing errors occur.

## Solution

In my opinion a good solution is **customize date serialization**, this way:

First, create a custom serializer for the `Date` class that formats dates as strings in a specific format. In this example, I&#39;ll use the ISO-8601 date format:

```java
import java.io.IOException;
import java.text.SimpleDateFormat;
import java.util.Date;

import com.fasterxml.jackson.core.JsonGenerator;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonSerializer;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.SerializerProvider;

public class CustomDateSerializer extends JsonSerializer&lt;Date&gt; {

    private static final SimpleDateFormat dateFormat = new SimpleDateFormat(&quot;yyyy-MM-dd&#39;T&#39;HH:mm:ss.SSSXXX&quot;);

    @Override
    public void serialize(Date value, JsonGenerator gen, SerializerProvider serializers) throws IOException {
        gen.writeString(dateFormat.format(value));
    }
}
```

Next, create a custom deserializer for the `Date` class that parses date strings in the same format:

```java
import java.io.IOException;
import java.text.ParseException;
import java.text.SimpleDateFormat;
import java.util.Date;

import com.fasterxml.jackson.core.JsonParser;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.DeserializationContext;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonDeserializer;

public class CustomDateDeserializer extends JsonDeserializer&lt;Date&gt; {

    private static final SimpleDateFormat dateFormat = new SimpleDateFormat(&quot;yyyy-MM-dd&#39;T&#39;HH:mm:ss.SSSXXX&quot;);

    @Override
    public Date deserialize(JsonParser p, DeserializationContext ctxt) throws IOException {
        String dateString = p.getText();
        try {
            return dateFormat.parse(dateString);
        } catch (ParseException e) {
            throw new IOException(&quot;Error parsing date: &quot; + dateString, e);
        }
    }
}
```

And then, annotate your `Date` fields in the `InputDto` class with the custom serializers and deserializers:

```java
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.annotation.JsonDeserialize;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.annotation.JsonSerialize;

public class InputDto {
    @JsonSerialize(using = CustomDateSerializer.class)
    @JsonDeserialize(using = CustomDateDeserializer.class)
    private Date startDate;

    @JsonSerialize(using = CustomDateSerializer.class)
    @JsonDeserialize(using = CustomDateDeserializer.class)
    private Date endDate;

    // getters and setters
}
```

